entries.snippet: Google DeepMind CEO Demis Hassabis emphasized the significant potential of artificial intelligence (AI) to enhance human health. In a statement shared on X (formerly Twitter), Hassabis noted that AI's role in accelerating drug discovery is already evident and could fundamentally change the development of new medicines. He specifically mentioned the work of Isomorphic Labs, a company he co-founded in 2021, which focuses on this area. His remarks come amid ongoing discussions around the broader societal effects of AI, particularly concerns about job displacement. Hassabis redirected attention to the long-term positive impacts of AI, particularly in healthcare, advocating for its transformative potential in improving human well-being.

entries.title: Google DeepMind CEO Demis Hassabis talks about his sleep routine that he agrees is unusual; but he also has a 'warning', sleeping ...
entries.snippet: In a video interview with Fortune, Google DeepMind CEO Demis Hassabis discussed his unconventional sleep habits, mentioning that he typically sleeps "very little," aiming for around six hours a night. He revealed that his day is divided into two distinct work sessions: one packed with back-to-back meetings during the day, followed by family time and dinner in the evening, and then additional work at night. While acknowledging his unusual routine, Hassabis also issued a "warning" regarding sleep, hinting at the potential downsides of reduced rest despite his long-standing practice of this schedule. The discussion reflects broader trends among tech leaders who often adopt atypical sleep patterns in pursuit of productivity.

entries.title: DeepMind's CEO does a 'second day' of work at night: 'I come alive at about 1 a.m.'
entries.snippet: Google DeepMind CEO Demis Hassabis shared insights into his unconventional work and sleep schedule during a video interview with Fortune. Hassabis, who co-founded DeepMind in 2010 and led it through its 2023 merger with Google Brain, revealed that he typically sleeps around six hours per night and splits his workday into two distinct segments. His daytime hours are packed with meetings, leaving little free time. After spending evenings with his family, Hassabis begins a second work shift around 10 p.m., focusing on deep thinking, creativity, and research until about 4 a.m. He noted that he has followed this schedule for about a decade and feels most mentally active around 1 a.m. His unusual routine mirrors that of other tech leaders such as Elon Musk and Marc Benioff, who have also adapted their sleep patterns to meet professional demands. Hassabis, along with colleague John Jumper, was awarded the 2024 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for his contributions to protein structure prediction.
